**RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation)**
- **RAG** — A technique that grounds LLM responses in real, verifiable external data by retrieving relevant document chunks before generating an answer, directly addressing the hallucination problem
- **Vector Embeddings** — High-dimensional mathematical representations that capture the semantic meaning of text, so that similar concepts are positioned close together in vector space — the core of AI-powered search
- **Vector Databases** — Specialised databases that store and enable fast similarity-based search over vector embeddings, linking them back to source documents (e.g. OpenSearch, Pinecone, Redis, Chroma, Aurora pgvector)
- **Retrieve & Generate API** — A single Bedrock API call that executes the complete RAG workflow end-to-end, maintains conversation context, and returns a grounded answer with source attribution
- **Retrieve API** — Returns only the relevant document chunks from a knowledge base without generating a response, giving you full control over how you construct and present the final answer
- **Hybrid Search** — Combines semantic vector search with traditional keyword matching in a single query, improving both recall (finding more relevant results) and precision (filtering out irrelevant ones)

**RAG vs Fine-tuning**
- **RAG** — The preferred choice when data changes frequently (news, policies, catalogues), when citations and traceability are required, or when cost and deployment speed are priorities
- **Fine-tuning** — The right approach when you need a specific tone, brand voice, or behavioural consistency, when your domain has specialised jargon, or when the model needs to learn a pattern rather than just retrieve information
- **Continued Pre-training** — Extends a model's pre-training using unlabelled domain-specific data to deepen its general knowledge of a field, as opposed to fine-tuning which uses labelled task-specific data for sharper task performance

